💖 LOVE POTIONS 💖
AD: GIFTED | Last week you would have seen from our stories that Otis made love potions as his valentines themed #invitationtoplay 💕 I didn’t get round to sharing the photos with you, but they’re too sweet to keep to myself so here they are!
Otis used his science kit that was gifted to him by @i_love_freebie for a #review. He absolutely loves water play so I knew it would be both successful and messy!
I put out lots of different textures for him (pompoms, sand, pluffle, and pasta) and a jug of water and just left him to mix them up to his heart’s content! He really enjoyed this activity a lot and it kept him very engaged. He was fascinated when the water started to turn pink when mixed with the coloured pasta. He poured his concoctions in and out of each test tube and back and forth into the jug. He also liked using the funnel and pipettes to move the water.
.
Science kit from @i_love_freebie #gifted
Coloured pasta from @lilbitsuk
Playfoam pluffle from @learningresourcesuk #gifted
Playmat from @munchkinandbearuk
.

.

.
.

💜 BABYCARE TENS 💜
Here are some photos you haven’t seen before: me in labour with Otis! I hope you don’t mind these #throwback photos, but we didn’t take many photos during labour with Eddison until I got into the pool so of course I had to put my TENS machine aside then, but I really want to talk to you about it!
.
That thing around my neck is my @babycaretens machine & has been my saviour during both my labours.
.
During labour with Otis: I used my TENS machine since being 3/4cm dilated up until I went into the pool. I found it a great relief & a distraction during contractions. The best thing was that I could stay mobile. Not only was I able to use it in the car on the way to the birthing centre, but it also allowed me to keep mobile in the room & walk around the hospital too. It created a pleasant pulsing sensation between contractions that helped me release endorphins to combat the pain & then when I had a contraction I pressed the “boost” button which gave me an extra surge of power against the pain. I found that I didn’t need to increase the intensity too much as contractions got worse because it was so effective. Although the TENS machine can be used alongside gas & air and pethadine, it of course can’t be used in water & so I had to turn it off at one point. I missed it then because I knew it had helped me hugely & also made me feel like I had some control over my contractions & my ability to push through them.
.
During labour with Eddison: I was really proud that I managed to make it to 8cm dilated with just my TENS machine alone & I found it so affective that I didn’t need to increase the depth & intensity of the pulses more than 5 (on a 0-15 scale on the machine). By using the TENS machine, I could also go up & down the hospital stairs numerous times and do lunges & squats to help move baby down without being restricted to the room. At 8cm I swapped it for the gas & air as I went into the birthing pool.
.
I would really recommend the @babycaretens to any pregnant woman as it’s a great drug-free pain relief that really does work. And it’s not just good for labour! You can also use it to treat arthritis, neck/back pain, period pain, sciatica etc.

🧪SLIME 🧪
AD: GIFTED | This week’s #invitationtoplay was super quick and easy to set up as Otis has very kindly been sent this slime kit to review from @i_love_freebie. His Daddy and I took it in turns supervising him closely with this set-up as there are lots of small bits, but Otis just loved it! He got really stuck into the slime and enjoyed squelching it in his hands. He then liked to add the coloured balls as well as gems to different coloured slime to create his own designs of it. As well as that he thought it was great fun to put the shape cutters into it too and he enjoyed cutting up the slime with the tools included. He liked to use the bamboo baby feeding spoons from @worldofbamboo and because of the silicone end, the little balls clung to it like it was magnetic - this was interesting for Otis!
Otis did use his “Otis’ masterpieces” board from @woodentreasureofficial initially, but soon realised he liked squelching the slime in his hands more so we will probably keep that mostly for play doh instead.
Lots of fun was had! I’d definitely recommend slime as a sensory aspect to introduce to toddler play set ups. I’m not sure why I just assumed it was for older kids 🤷🏻‍♀️
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

💙 BROTHERHOOD 💙
“You and me... we’re in a club now!” - UP
And what a club brotherhood is 😍 I absolutely love watching Otis with his baby brother. He had bonded with him so much and it blows me away how much he loves having him around. I knew that Eddison’s arrival would go 1 of 2 ways for Otis and I’m just so grateful that a month into his new role as big brother, the novelty hasn’t worn off! I didn’t think my heart could love Otis any more than it did already, but seeing him dote on Eddison seems to have opened a door in my heart to a room that I didn’t even know existed and it’s full of new love! 🥰 fingers crossed that Otis’ adoration for Eddison long continues!!
.

👩🏻 MAKE-UP BAG ESSENTIALS 👩🏻
AD: GIFTED | What are the essential items in your make-up bag? For me a good base is a priority to boost my confidence and so I was really keen to try out the foundation that I was kindly #gifted from @seren_ity.dream. I chose the blur effect lifting foundation in beige as I was intrigued by its promise to “superbly cover imperfections” and also because it’s a much cheaper alternative to the MAC foundations I usually buy. I have really enjoyed trying it out and seeing how my skin reacts to it. Even with the hormone inbalance after just having a baby, my skin hasn’t broken out once with the new product, it’s stayed really healthy. As soon as I tried the foundation for the first time I noticed the pleasant scent to it and also realised that although the coverage it provides is fantastic, it doesn’t feel too heavy on my skin and I feel like my skin can still breathe. Because of this it’s easy to blend too and doesn’t leave any foundation lines. It does exactly what it says in its product description: “it guarantees flawless, youthful and a natural look without the mask effect”. It makes my skin look soft and not shiny at all. I also love that it’s not tested on animals. I’d absolutely recommend this foundation, you should give it a go!
.
.
.
.
.

👣 FOOTPRINTS 👣
“The butterflies they used to give me turned into tiny baby feet”.
AD: GIFTED | I’m not sure what it is about baby feet, but I just love to kiss them 🤷🏻‍♀️ even now he’s a toddler I can’t help kissing Otis’ feet either when I get him dressed. When both boys were born I have been fascinated by their perfect little feet and tiny toes and in awe that my body grew them like that.
@lucycoggle Baby footprint kits makes sure I have some way of preserving the memory of their gorgeous, little feet forever before one day they turn into sweaty teenager feet that I can’t bare to be around 🙈 I am so, so pleased with how their footprints turned out and I’m excited to put them up on the wall, they really are pieces of art and so much more special than standard footprint kits.
.
(Eddison’s bib and leggings are from @claybearofficial 🐥
Otis’ leggings are from @curlytwirlytots 🐇)

👣 FOOTPRINTS 👣 
AD: GIFTED | We all know our little ones leave footprints all over our hearts, but it’s easy to forget to keep a physical record of their growing footprints in the mayhem that can sometimes be family life!
.
This is why I love @lucycoggle and her footprint kits because she makes it easy! Her illustrations are absolutely beautiful and the kits are designed so little ones add their footprints as feet onto the animal of their (or your!) choice. Each kit comes with 2 prints of the animal as well as clear instructions and some baby safe ink. I think it’s great that it comes with 2 sheets because it not only allows room for error in case you make a mistake, but it also means you could frame one sheet on the wall and either gift the other to a family member or put it in a keepsake box. It was so much quicker and easier to do than I imagined and within 10 minutes I was left with the most beautiful keepsakes from both my boys. (Perfect Mother’s Day gift idea - send your partners to the @lucycoggle page!!)
.
I really want to point out that these kits aren’t just for babies! They come in a variety of sizes to adjust to your little one’s shoe size. I did this with Otis first and he absolutely loved it, he was so proud of it afterwards and excited to see the bunny have feet! He then helped me do Eddison’s prints by putting the ink on his foot as I held him.  I love that I can use these kits not only as a milestone keepsake for Eddison, but also as a keepsake for Otis too as a toddler and it’s a great way of getting him involved. I can’t wait to share our finished prints with you later!
.
@lucycoggle has so many beautiful animal designs to choose from. We chose a bunny for Otis for his Peter Rabbit nursery and of course Eddison had to have the duck!
What one would you choose? 🐻 🐼 🐧 🦉🐥
.

1️⃣ 1 MONTH OLD 1️⃣
AD: GIFTED|
To our Littlest Pea, Eddison
Today you are 1 month old. Already? How?! I just don’t know. I feel like I only gave birth to you last week, I’m so not ready for you to be 1 month old already. This has genuinely been the fastest month of my life and I feel confused trying to work out how it went so fast. I wasn’t prepared to lose the days so quick and every day I see changes in you. I’m so excited to see you grow up though and make memories with you, but I wish time wouldn’t steal these moments of you being so small away from us.
Not only has it been the fastest month of my life, but it’s been the most special too. You have brought so much happiness and excitement to us already and brought out a new side to Otis too, in his role as your big brother. We all adore you and love you so much!
Love from Mummy xx
.

❤️ MUMMY’S LITTLE VALENTINES ❤️
Love is......
...finding my own happiness in your happiness.
... wanting to treasure and capture every moment with you.
... letting you dominate the topic of every adult conversation I have, even if it means talking about poop!
... feeling like I want a break, but as soon as I leave the room I miss you.
... being so proud of your every achievement, no matter how small.
... knowing I would give you my everything in a heartbeat.
... breaking my heart over you growing out of yet another size of clothing.
... wanting to show off photos of you to everyone, even someone I meet on a train.
... beating myself up if you fall and I don’t manage to catch you in time.
... holding you in the warmest cuddles and never wanting the moment to end.
... planning my whole social life around what activities you would enjoy.
.... YOU. That’s what love is.... you!
.

🏥 HOSPITAL STAY 🏥
AD: GIFTED | After the initial panic during the first 2 hours we spent at hospital, things went really calm & I was really well looked after (with thanks to my midwife who had made sure all staff knew I’d had a bad experience before & put motions in place to protect me). They allowed my dad in the room with us, then they allowed all my siblings to visit 3 hours after we arrived (against hospital rules), nobody rushed my visitors out or interrupted their visit, I wasn’t rushed out of the room to go to the ward, I was given plenty of time for a shower, Andy & I both got to eat before we went to the ward, the ward we were taken to was the birth centre ward instead of the normal ward I was meant to go to, so it was just us & one other lady and her baby in the room... the staff were kind & patient.
.
To add to this great experience I of course had my @_motherbe pre-packed hospital bag with me that made sure I had everything I needed. I’d managed to leave my slippers at the birth centre, but there were some spare flip flops in my case! I also enjoyed using my fresh, new products in my shower & gave myself a little pamper with the face cleanser & moisturiser too. I also made good use out of the maternity pads, breast pads, hair brush, toothbrush & toothpaste. I had used the large drawstring bag to store my PJs & clothes so they were easy to find and when I got dressed then I used the bag as a laundry bag for my dirty clothes. The toy bunny kept Eddison company on the ward & the generous sized pack of nappies & wipes were fab for keeping him clean. The case had also included muslins, sleepsuits, vests & a hat... literally everything I needed from a labour bag! Having this pre-packed case from @_motherbe really did prepare me for those first days with a new baby & I’m so grateful for how stress-free it made preparing for labour!
The best part about it: it was a suitcase on wheels! As you can see we had our hands full leaving the hospital & it would have been too much to carry if the case had been a bag. The fact it was a case made life so much easier. It’s ideal for those who have caesareans too as doesn’t have to be carried!
Thank you @_motherbe ❤️

❤️My labour story | part 4: after birth❤️
Please note: this comes with a trigger warning of trauma. Please don’t read if you’re pregnant & feel vulnerable
.
I found this hard to write so I’m just going to come out & say the worst bit: I thought my baby was stillborn.
In the pool I felt an instant rush of love as I looked at my perfect baby boy, in my arms finally & I was relieved labour was over. I’d had my perfect water birth & I was elated. But in the few seconds I spent looking at him I realised something was wrong. My floppy, purple, silent baby was not breathing. I felt sick & frozen with fear as the resus team came in, Eddison was cut from me quickly & my baby was taken to the other side of the room. I couldn’t see him, but got a glimpse of him being rubbed in a towel like a puppy. I was asked to get out of the pool, but as I stood blood just fell & surrounded me. I haemorrhaged & lost approx 1.2 litres of blood. As I stood I looked to Andy who was in the middle of me & Eddison, looking back & forth between us both & crying so hard. He looked terrified & his face haunts me still. Eddison came round quickly though & was given straight to Andy for skin to skin.
.
What happened next was a blur. I was taken to the bed & Kate gave me the choice to push the placenta out or for it to be pulled. After the trauma of it being pulled last time & the cord snapping, I pushed as much as I could before answering Kate. It came out fine. Kate calmly told me the plan to go to hospital & she’d come with me, not to worry & that I’d be ok. But I didn’t feel ok, I felt terrified. I thought I would die & I thought of Otis & Eddison being left without a Mum.
.
The paramedics were quickly in the room & were lovely with me. Eddison was laid on the bed next to me for some skin to skin before he was taken by his ambulance to hospital (with Andy) & I was taken in another one. Being separated from him was torture.
.
The tone changed at hospital; the staff seemed flustered & dramatic & prodded/poked me unnecessarily. This led me to ask that they keep Andy outside the room as I didn’t want him to panic more.
.
This photo was my first proper hold of my baby, over 2 hours after his birth.

❤️My labour story| Part 3: Eddison’s birth❤️
When Kate said “I’ve got good news for you Holly” I cried. Then I smiled & then I laughed. Being told i’d progressed to 8cm made me emotional with relief. I also felt proud I’d managed with just my TENS machine. Kate asked if I wanted to get in the pool & I couldn’t get in quick enough. I put my swimwear on, swapped my TENS machine for gas & air & by 12:15, I was in the pool. I was smiley & felt ridiculously calm & happy for someone so far into labour. Kate did my hair for me & I felt ready for the next stage. Inbetween contractions I snacked, chatted, laughed, listened to my music & enjoyed the company of my team. I watched videos of Otis playing sent by my friend.
.
Andy & my Mam took turns being with me, held my hand & talked me through contractions. After each contraction Kate listened to baby & reassured me that all was ok. As contractions got closer & longer I got really sleepy & also dizzy from the gas & air. I worried Kate would take me out of the pool so I fought hard to stay awake.
.
The hours went fast & I soon thought (and said!) “I can’t do this” & “it hurts too much”. Id been sat in the water with my back to the side of the pool. Then suddenly my body started pushing & I instinctively swung myself around so I faced outside the pool, held the handles, knelt upright & told everyone “I’m pushing!”. It caught me by surprise. Kate encouraged me to listen to my body & push as I needed to.
.
I asked Mam to take a photo of my baby still in the waters & she told Andy to look too so my dad sat infront of me & helped me through. He told me “you’re doing amazing” & gave me strength & encouragement. I pushed for less than 30 mins before Eddison’s head was out. Eddison was born in his waters so Kate broke them as his head emerged. 3 long minutes until the next contraction then I pushed his body out. My baby appeared in the water in front of me & Kate helped lift him into my arms & she held us both.
.
We’d agreed Andy would announce gender, but I couldn’t resist & looked myself & told them all “it’s a boy!”. I’d had the perfect water birth & I looked down at my perfect baby son with love.
Then things got complicated...

❤️My labour story| Part 2: established labour ❤️
Thurs 16th Jan.
We met Julie (midwife) at the birth centre at 5am. The room was set up for us: dim lighting: sensory lights & the pool had been filled. After an examination she said “fantastic, you’re well over halfway” & “your baby will be born today”. I didn’t know how many cm dilated I was & this bothered me at first, but actually it was great not to obsess over a number. I was relieved not to be sent home.
.
I continued to labour without pain relief, bounced on the ball & Andy set up my playlist. At 7am I finally had a show. Mam & Dad arrived at 7:30am and shortly after, my Mam attached my TENS machine to me. At 8am Julie was replaced by my midwife Kate. The change slowed my contractions down, but they picked up again as I quickly developed a trust in Kate.
.
I was examined at 9:30am to check on progress & was devastated to be told I was 5cm & had been 5cm when we arrived 4 hours ago. Baby still hadn’t moved down or gotten in the right position. We discussed my options which included breaking my waters & then I broke down. I completely lost myself for a bit because that’s what happened with Otis: I didn’t progress, my waters were broken & because there was meconium in them, at 8cm we were blue lighted to hospital where I had a bad experience & poor care. And I knew because Eddison was overdue, there was even more of a risk of him pooping. I cried. A lot. And I couldn’t stop.
.
Kate knew how vulnerable I was about the thought of going back to the hospital so offered to re-examine me in 2 hours instead of intervening. My Mam took me out for a walk around the birth centre & a reality check as I had totally lost emotional control. She helped me re-focus & with her encouragement I spent time lunging & doing squats on the stairs to encourage baby to move down.
.
When I returned to the room I decided to “put my game face on” & put my full face of make-up on so that it would stop me crying again. It worked, I suddenly felt empowered. I put on my playlist, my mam gave me a nice hand & arm massage & Kate put some calming essentials oils in the diffuser.
At 12:00 I was re-examined & was shocked to hear I was now 8cm!

❤️My labour story: Part 1 | the latent phase ❤️
Weds 15th Jan
I woke up at 3:45am with some cramping. This continued all morning & at 6:42am I rang my Mam. Andy got up at 7:45am & I told him I’d been cramping for 4 hours & my Mam was on her way via train. He got Otis ready for nursery then said “should I pick your Mum up from the station then go to work?” (😂 in denial I think!) I told him it would be best if he stayed home today!
My Mam arrived at 10am & then my cramps (I wouldn’t call them contractions) slowed down until 12:00 when they stopped. I felt gutted. My Mam suggested we get out of the house for a bit so we went shopping & had lunch. Whilst out the cramping returned & had definitely intensified. By the time we got home at 5pm (after picking Otis up) they were more frequent & still intense.
The contractions (there was no doubt in calling them that now) continued through the evening & my team helped get me through: Mam gave me a back massage with the help of Otis, Andy gave me a hand massage, Dad recorded the times of contractions...
I took 1 paracetamol at 9:40pm - my 1st pain relief. I found strength through the affirmations I’d put on the wall, in particular the ones that said “my body was designed to do this” & “I can breathe through this contraction”. I rang the homebirth team at 11:13pm to tell them I was in labour & that I wanted to go to the freestanding birth centre. I said I was coping ok at home for now, but would ring back when I needed to. At midnight I sent everyone to bed knowing I’d need them to have energy the next day. At 00:30 I laid down on the sofa to rest, but every contraction made me throw myself upright again. At 1:30-2:30am I went in the bath to ease the pains, but ended up taking 2 more paracetamol at 2:50am.
Inbetween laying down & having a bath, my labour space at home became really valuable to me. I bounced on my ball alone with the lights off, candles lit & my labour playlist on.
At 3:12am I called the homebirth team again to explain I was now struggling to cope & we planned to meet at the birth centre. Andy and I got ready & went to the birth centre. Mam & Dad stayed with Otis until 6am then took him to my friend’s house.

👶🏼 THE BABY SHOW 👶🏼 GIFTED | #throwbacktuesday (yeah, it’s a thing now) to when we attended @thebabyshow in October and Eddison was still cosy in my tummy!

💙MUMMY’S BOYS 💙
So today is our first full day alone together, just my boys and I! I’ve been anxious about the husband returning to work, not just because it means I’m alone with the boys, but also because I worry about what he’s returning to. He hasn’t had the most stress-free paternity leave and actually has spent quite a bit of it answering emails, taking phone calls, chasing things up and even going into work and attending work events. The boys and I have had a lovely, slow and relaxing morning and I’ve just been thinking about Mr Pea and hoping his morning has been good too!
Don’t get me wrong, being home alone with a toddler and a newborn hasn’t been easy this morning. Otis may have eaten chocolate and Pringles before I managed to finish doing his cornflakes. Eddison has had one poop explosion and I’ve already changed 5 nappies and breastfed 6 times since their Daddy left for work.  I haven’t put a load of washing on as planned or washed any dishes.
BUT we have managed to all get dressed, Otis and I danced to the lion king soundtrack, we all had some snuggles in bed and I even managed to watch love island before Otis woke up (priorities 😂)! So it appears today is turning into a “just do what I can and don’t stress” kinda day and I plan on soaking in all the happiness that motherhood brings me today 😊

💙 “LET’S TALK ABOUT YOUR NEW BABY BROTHER” 💙
AD: GIFTED | It’s no secret that we really enjoyed working with @helenlacey_author to help spread the word about her amazing book “let’s talk to mummy’s tummy” so when she got in touch offering to send Otis her new book, I absolutely jumped at the chance! I was so impressed with her first book and so grateful for how it helped explain my pregnancy to Otis, I knew that the new book was going to be good!
.
This afternoon Otis and I read some of the new book together in the company of Eddison too. It’s called “let’s talk about your new baby brother or sister” and is a siblings’ guide to the next 24 months with their new baby brother / sister. I absolutely love it because it helps to explain things to Otis that I sometimes forget; such as why Eddison cries and why he’s so sleepy as well as promising him that as Eddison grows they will have lots of happy times together too. I cross-referenced the book with pages from the previous book which gave us ideas for activities we can do together to help the boys bond and also what memories they may make together in the future, for example swimming together, playing catch, playing on swings together etc.
.
The new book continues to talk about developmental milestones that Eddison will reach and suggests more activities that Otis can do with him as he grows.
Both books are beautifully illustrated with gentle and soft pictures that echo the tone of the information provided to toddlers. Otis really loves looking at the pictures and talking to me about them, pointing out that the breastfeeding baby was having milk and another baby was crying and one was sleeping etc. He saw pictures of older siblings holding the new babies and he wanted to hold Eddison too.
.
I really loved reading the start of this book with Otis and I know that it definitely will lay the foundation for a close and harmonious relationship between the boys. I’d 100% recommend it to anyone who is due or has recently had a second / third baby etc!
Thank you @helenlacey_author 💙
